(iii) we should think about our methods. Mapping against genome graphs seems promising but has not really been adopted in human genomics. We can also incorporate  mapping bias in genotype calling/likelihoods. The effect is somewhat predictable so we can make use of that fact 5/n

So how can we deal with this? (i) awareness is important so be critical about your own results. Especially when dealing with fine scale differences and data from different sources. (ii) we propose some filters which help reducing the effect but don't fully eliminate it. 4/n

More seriously, my position here about the genetics of IQ and educational attainment is *NOT* that there is no genetics to it, nor fluctuation in populations, it is that other traits, in particular skin pigmentation, don't predict the genetics IQ traits. Same with height.

Unsurprisingly African pygmies have- wait for it - quite complex population history+when the trait (height) is used as part of the definition everything gets very circular. To map this to this discussion people with low educational attainment will have low educational attainment

I know some people will now mention "African pygmies" with my analogy with height. There are definitely people in Africa with varying height (also in Europe - we don't talk about Spanish pygmies...) and there are many genetic components to this - absolutely right

At this level it is complex to completely rule out any "weak" selection - but IQ/Educational Attainment is *not* the phenotype for us to build up theory on. The community made a big mess of this in height recently+its complex to model everything even on "straightforward" traits

For me - stop thinking about humans as "groups of people" and start thinking about them as "people with complex family histories", and everyone has a complex family history, and all our family histories (across the *entire planet*) become one family history pretty quickly.

As my long time followers know, I bang on about the fact that European is itself an older mixing process (Bronze age Steppe people, Anatolian Farmers and "European" hunter gathers) with different combinations and complex expansions (Finland) or refuges (Sardinia)

Although in modern society we often have the term "mixed race" to describe people who have in the latest generation have parents from two different self-identified ethnic groups, these groups themselves are complex mixtures as in fact are for example "Europeans"

<< due to indentured workers from South Asia (when the British Empire banned slavery they allowed something pretty close to it). Hispanics vary in European ancestry from 90% through to 10%, with both native american and african ancestries.

This has given rise to people with complex mixed ancestries - African Americans will have between 5 to 50% European ancestry (median 15-20%), rest combinations of different parts of Africa (itself very complex); Afro-Caribbeans even more complex >>

There are some particular sets of people we assigned ethnicity labels to understand in more detail - Hispanics in America; Afro-Caribbeans (in the Caribbean and UK) and African-America. All these are due to 17th-19th Century movements of people, many forced by slavery

It's been true all the time, and although we can also see concentrations of when mutations arose in particular geographic locations (eg, mutations that arose in Cornwall vs Devon) that "fine resolution" of people is not incompatible with broad and big complex global mixing

Furthermore, humans have always been a mobile species with a great fondness for having sex (like all other species). This is true now (take London, New York); it was true in the 19th century, sometimes forced movement by slavery; it was true in the bronze age.

The genome sampling is another random process on top of this family tree process, and makes the genome inheritance even more complex and random - go back 6 or so generations and one has ancestors who you share no DNA with.

But - broadly IQ/Educational Attainment measures can be used - and, with scrupulous care of this whole environment question, can be used with genetics.
This is another rabbit hole to go down around Social Genetic Effects - I recommend @AlexTISYoung's work here and also more generally @AmelieBaud's work here. It's great stuff.

And then, finally, a clear environmental aspect to the individual is their direct family - their parents. This is both a headache for geneticists (families providing environment) and an opportunity (they can study the creation of this environment using genetics)

And its not just about "geographic" environment. I grew up in a family in Notting Hill in London, next door to many Afro-Carribbean families but there is no doubt at all I had a very different environment.

This is a slightly silly example which is obvious, but one does have to get slightly twitchy about more subtle environment. Is the environment in Kopenhagen the same as Jutland? Or Newcastle or Bath? Or Uppsala to Gotland?

Notice though this homogenous environment. Environment plays a big role here. There are clear things - rank people across *Europe* on their English or French ability you will get a very different genetics vs non genetics compared to ranking inside a country (England, France)

Not easy, but after some iterations (we test it against real datasets using @CSoneson's countsimQC package + some pseudobulk-level dispersion-mean plots to check sample-sample variability), I think we have a very flexible simulation .. https://t.co/LTUcqFwTg6

Turns out there are many ways to do this: mixed models, "pseudobulks", comparing distributions. So, we wanted to survey how to best do this. First hurdle was simulating data in a way that we maintain properties of scRNA-seq but also considers sample-to-sample variability.

We call this *differential state* analysis. The cells are already organized into "types" (ok, this requires a computational analysis) and we look for differences in expression in the cells of treated samples versus cells of control samples; we do this one subpopulation at a time.

meaning, we have a proper replicated experiment, multi-sample, multi-condition and we are profiling multiple cell subpopulations (e.g., tissue, blood, etc.). Here, we're interested in following a subpopulation (e.g., T cells) across samples, say to compare treated vs control.

So .. people talk a lot about differential expression in scRNA-seq data, but from what I can tell, most of it is about how to find marker genes. That's indeed interesting, but not what we are on about here. Here, we're interested in *sample-level* comparisons of scRNA-seq ..

These graphs may look a bit silly with me scribbling on them, so here's a real one showing SA's new battery storage working the same way. I also include a big picture SA power graph to make one point: even a huge battery stores basically nothing compared to what a grid uses. https://t.co/qW5Nwc1A08

To do it we store the red and release it as green. I will be generous and assume 100% efficient storage that never needs replacement. For reference, batteries could be 90% efficient and last a few decades. Grid hydrogen is like under 50% from memory. Pumped hydro is like 80ish. https://t.co/sABiHP62wm

Storage is about energy capacity mostly, though most pop science pages report power capacity (the easiest bit!) We will look at the real challenge. Let's for sake of it imagine making Aus's WHOLE current wind capacity generate 1.5 GW of dispatchable energy (1 small nuclear plant) https://t.co/K4dJz08AlW
So, maybe storage is a better solution. Here's a great way to picture how storage works in a grid ... https://t.co/ydKFRaWjff

To do what the nuclear could via this over-production approach, wind would need quite a bit of scaling. Here the troughs are at 0.4 GW. To make, say, 10 GW means building 10/.4 = 25 times our current capacity. So ~2350 wind farms (!). Or four medium nuclear facilities. https://t.co/Y99zoCJt1p

One way to do it is make more wind turbines, so the minimum generated is always more than demand. If we build more turbines, capacity moves approximately proportionally, so we essentially re-scale the Y-axis. Here's 1/2 capacity in red and 2x capacity in green to illustrate. https://t.co/mxYoQCIArR

Now, to deliver dispatchable ("on demand, anytime") energy like nuclear, wind needs to exceed demand &/or use storage. A good test is to see if it can follow the shape of the demanded amount. To contribute its current ~5% dispatchably, it'd look something like this blue wiggle. https://t.co/s5C73T2qkr

To give us an idea what wind is like, here's last month. It's the total over all of Australia. As you can see, it hovers around 2 GW of energy. For comparison, that's about what one biggish nuclear or coal power station makes. But coal sucks balls so we're talking nuclear today. https://t.co/5nHn12fyHR

Before focusing on wind, let's look at the big picture power for generation in Aus, right now! Just to get us in the mood, note that the mean wind has sort of died currently and the sun has set (red). So you'd need storage if you didn't have fossils (blue). https://t.co/4lsulBl37o

fin/ One could see this as the intellectual property equivalent of holding someone hostage. Any scientific community doing business with IEEE should reconsider its priorities.

14/ What @IEEEorg appears to be pulling off is harmful to scientific discourse. Forcing authors to hand over ownership of the copyright if they want to share their work as a preprint as it is being considered for publication at an IEEE publication, is completely unacceptable.

13/ That FAQ only talks about ‚ÄúAccepted Versions of Papers‚Äù and gives the impression that copyright transfer to IEEE only takes places after an article has been accepted for publication. I am not sure if the other scenarios are an intentional omission, but this is confusing. https://t.co/CslQHZtB44

12/ However, things get even more murky when consulting other guidelines put out by IEEE, such as their ‚ÄúFAQ on Intellectual Property Rights for IEEE Authors‚Äù (https://t.co/xy6p4yqHqp), which is linked from IEEE Intellectual Property Rights website: https://t.co/Joqnuzc0kS.

11/ Note that the rules in the @IEEEorg PSPB Operations Manual are even more stringent, including cases where a preprint was posted *before* submission to an IEEE publication venue. The posting policy page only mentions situations in which the preprint is posted after submission.

10/ The above policies seems to be backed by the ‚ÄúOperations Manual‚Äù (https://t.co/JAdhH25BWN) of the IEEE Publication Services & Products Board, which are ‚ÄúComprehensive guidelines for every aspect of publishing with IEEE‚Äù.  See Section 8.1.9 D. E-prints: https://t.co/AyFK0Ihz7J https://t.co/8j0PebsbB1
9/ And by the way, all of this not only applies to cases in which you posted on @arxiv or another preprint server, it also applies to manuscripts that you posted on your own personal website.

8/ In case you are now thinking that I might have misinterpreted what this rule applies to, make sure to read the rest of that page. It also lists almost identical rules for ‚ÄúAuthor-submitted article‚Äù, ‚ÄúAccepted article‚Äù, and ‚ÄúFinal published article‚Äù: https://t.co/1F2e3H2Pdt

7/ That means that if your article gets rejected and you want to resubmit it to a different venue, you will need to ask IEEE for permission first. Even if you just want to reuse a figure from your rejected paper in another publication, you will have to ask for permission.

6/ Furthermore, the page states that authors need to include the a copyright notice, that prohibits any but personal use of the material in the preprint without permission from IEEE. https://t.co/gUcezlrIGp

5/ That is quite curious, given that  authors generally don‚Äôt sign a license agreement until after their manuscript has been accepted. I am not sure how a court of law would interpret this copyright transfer that happens without explicit consent of the author. Lawyers? Comments?

4/ Under ‚ÄúPreprints‚Äù, the page states that ‚ÄúIf the preprint is posted after the article is submitted to IEEE for peer review, IEEE must be credited as the copyright holder [‚Ä¶]‚Äù. Ahem?! https://t.co/cvXc2A020s

3/ I came across their preprint policy on the ‚ÄúIEEE Author Center Guidelines and Policies‚Äù website, which has a page called ‚ÄúPolicy: Posting Your Journal Article‚Äù: https://t.co/1F2e3H2Pdt. That page provides posting policies for ‚Äúeprint‚Äù, ‚Äúpreprint‚Äù, ‚Äúaccepted article‚Äù, etc.

2/ This is long before your paper has been reviewed or you have any idea if your paper will be accepted. I hope that organizations like @OSFramework, @ASAPbio_, @biorxivpreprint, & @arxiv take notice of this publishing model, which has significant implications for #preprints.

1/ I want to share a pretty shocking discovery that I made in @IEEEorg‚Äôs #preprint rules. In essence, as I understand it, IEEE claims the copyright to your preprint *as soon as you submit* the manuscript to an IEEE publication venue. Read that again, *as soon as you submit*!

So if immigrating was so awful 30 years ago and those paths are shut, I can only imagine what it's like now for new immigrants. Then again it's not really about the law.In conclusion: Xenophobia and Nationalism has never created a great nation but have sunk many a great nation.

It's not just unskilled labor coming in... there's plenty of skilled labor we need because we just don't produce enough. "The skills gap is due, in part, to the sheer number of baby boomers retiring" https://t.co/JGii2mhMgu

But then I'll hear "yeah but you came here with a job..." you know there are plenty of jobs here. Remember 2012 when crops rotted? "farmers were about 40 percent short of the number of workers they needed to harvest last year‚Äôs crop." https://t.co/TXgflfhvD4

Newly minted little pinkish looking "green" cards that gave us back our life, a mountain of debt took years for us to crawl from under. The INS guy? turned out he got fired later for basically being a racist prick. We weren't his first victims. By now Ive lost two years of school

Finally 14mo since first interview we get a new interview, my mom is nearly falling apart because again, the alternative is a country with zero job prospect. Lady this time says "I don't know why this was denied, I reviewed this and everything is in order, welcome to America."

Luckly the internet exists in 1994 and she's able to work remotely! My sister flies to USA to take over office in Miami, we rent a studio apartment near friends in Recife, I attend an international school $$$$ because I can no longer function in Brazilian school system.

absolutely everything was above board. We really had a job, we really paid taxes, we really loved and still love America. Our visas are cancelled, now I'm stuck in Brazil, losing another year of school while our petition for a new interview goes through system... again, more $$$

She finally got her work visa, and the green card/residency process began. Again $$$$$, time, by now I'm in High School. We finally get an interview and need to return to Brazil to have it done. It was denied because INS dude mistook her nervousness for lying. Grilled her for 1hr

My grades were entered into evidence! exemplary student! People got interviewed for her job and if at anytime someone more qualified interviewed it was over. Luckly my mother had a very specific skillset unmatched.

Interestingly, male clinician gender, lower age of Medicare beneficiaries, percentage of Female beneficiaries seen by a clinician, and lower HCC risk score were all correlated with *increased* opioid claim volume.
However, we did identify extreme cases of opioid prescribing, including a clinician with 502 opioid claims prescribed in one year and another whose opioid claims during one year cost over $40,000.

We found that while opioid claim volume among OMFS has *increased* over time, mean opioid claims per beneficiary and days supply per opioid claim per beneficiary both decreased, indicating *more responsible prescribing* to a larger Medicare population.

We used @CMSgov data from 2013-2017 to 1) study changes in opioid claim volume, mean prescriptions per pt, and opioid days supply per claim, 2) identify correlates of high opioid prescription volume, and 3) compare opioid volume by state and by surgical subspecialty.

I‚Äôve got no solutions beyond the stop-gap of pluralising ‚Äúancestries‚Äù - ‚ÄúEuropean ancestries‚Äù, ‚ÄúAfrican-American ancestries‚Äù, ‚ÄúHan Chinese ancestries‚Äù. It‚Äôs not ideal but it‚Äôs a start. Discussion welcome!

So we both need to create good language about complex tree like structures for humans (and other species), and have easy ways to communicate with a broad audience that neither compromises key points in this model but is also accessible and ideally fits into everyday life

These labels (ethnic groups) are so wired into our discourse it is both hard as a scientist to disentangle yourself from this framework, hard not to use everyday words (‚ÄúAfrican-American‚Äù) when communicating - there is a big cross current here between accuracy and accessibility
Final fourth point. Society uses the ‚Äúset and label‚Äù approach *a lot*, mainly using cultural cues but with enough genetics (skin pigmentation, hair) to make it very messy.

That said, the assignment of alleles at meiosis is one of the most random things in biology (exceptions as always - GAGE genes take a bow - but mainly). This means using family based studies is another key way to attack this

This harsh, unfair, inequitable reality is wrong on a societal scale and plain frustrating for the science of genetics - it‚Äôs why studying human genetics in sub Saharan Africa will give us a different view (though not there is a ‚Äúflat equitable society‚Äù anywhere)

The other aspect is that a ‚Äúcomplex tree‚Äù perspective does not magic away discrimination in society and when we do studies we need to ‚Äúremove as many confounders as possible‚Äù and take ‚Äúas homogeneous environment as possible‚Äù - our ‚Äúwell mixed subsets‚Äù also are useful for this

That bias has been mainly the part of the tree geographically associated with Europe or recently migrated people whose ancestry (heavily) biased to connect to this part of this tree. To get at genetics of humans better we need more even sampling of the tree

Third point is moving from a set-and-label perspective to a tree perspective doesn‚Äôt magically solve the poor sampling of genetics we‚Äôve had over the last three decades. In the new terminology we‚Äôve been very biased in the parts of the tree we‚Äôve been sampling

The ‚Äútreat everyone as having complex ancestries‚Äù is therefore both more complete (and therefore worldwide equitable) but also better at doing the straightforward handling the ‚Äúaverage White British‚Äù or ‚Äúaverage European American‚Äù. What‚Äôs not to like?

the current ‚Äúwell mixed‚Äù labels are less well mixed when one takes everyone - many confidently self identified Europeans have complex admixed ancestries - ie, the set-and-label model doesn‚Äôt even work that well even in the groups it sounds like it should

This is bonkers; firstly there are *alot* of admixed people in this model, some with their own labels (‚ÄúAfrican Americans‚Äù, ‚ÄúHispanics‚Äù, ‚ÄúWhite South Africans‚Äù, ‚ÄúAfro Caribbean‚Äù); pushing a good fraction of our society into a ‚Äúhard to model‚Äù category is not going to work well

So if you have suffered from a #TBI, you're not alone. Be kind to yourself. You're still capable of kicking ass at grad school or your career or life in general!

I thought it was my personality and I just sucked at getting things done. She said brains take a lot more time to heal than we think they do and that it's ok to acknowledge that and be forgiving with ourselves. And find alternative ways to cope.

She pointed out that it's not uncommon for people with TBI to have trouble focusing on tasks, as well as the other things I described- difficulties accessing my vocabulary, light sensitivity, etc. Things that make #gradschool hard sometimes!
I often forget about my concussions (lol, brain injury jokes) because it happened, I took a frustrating week off school and work, and then things went back to normal (but they really didn't.)

Insightful moment in therapy this morning when I was talking about having difficulties focusing on a single task at a time and following it to completion. My counselor asked if I've ever had a concussion or other TBI. I've had four- the most recent being about 8 months ago.

Genes associated with anorexia nervosa were enriched for expression in the brain, and particularly medium spiny neurons and pyramidal neurons from hippocampal CA1 (in mice). 5/9 https://t.co/ptT94UlUNE

Altogether, the manuscript address with what I would define ‚Äúhighly accurate data and analysis‚Äù the key question: what is the fraction of lncRNAs that shows some function? I personally believe that 40% is conservative.But in essence, many lncRNAs are likely to be functional.

In the used CAGE protocol, there is no PCR before loading in the Illumina sequencer; although the number is not as high as perturb-seq, our approach is complementary because it measure with high accuracy all perturbations that happened to biological networks after lncRNAs KD.

Measuring phenotype is a challenge. Even though we use only human dermal fibroblasts, we measure some phenotype for ~40% of the lncRNAs. In particular, non-amplified CAGE shows that perturbation (KD) of lncRNAs cause changes in transcriptional/regulatory networks.

At the beginning of the millennium, others and us identified many lncRNAs. New exciting biological paradigms emerge from analysis of functional lncRNAs only when we can know their functions.In the #FANTOM6 pilot project we tested functions of 285 lncRNAshttps://t.co/xoDHiRafUM

Before Indio Rose was released, some of the genetics escaped into the breeding community as "P20". Many different new tomato varieties have arisen in the years since with genetics from P20 or Indigo Rose.

The genetics responsible for this lovely purple color were bred into domesticated tomatoes from wild (generally inedible) tomato species way back in the 1960s. More recent work at OSU brought these traits into the variety "Indigo Rose", the 1st available variety with this color.

This complex endless move, mix, move again (over centuries) is the hallmark of humans across our history and is why the business of trying to carve out sets of people as useful genetic groupings will simply not work well.

It's probably the case that the movement of people today (certainly the individual movement) is more than in pre-history, but human gene flow happened alot (again in the timescale of 10 or so generations - plenty of time to do this)

This means groupings of people we feel socially quite confident on ("Europeans", "Zulu","Tamil") are not some sort of indigenous "out of Africa people moved to X and then stayed there until advent of sea born trade" - this is not how human pre-history works out.

These gene movements are just some; they are large many modern day Europeans have majority Yamana related haplotypes (but not all). We are likely to find many more both due to sequencing many more living people and ancient bones. It's an exciting time.
Then there is the complex waves of migration into the Americas via the Bearing straight, where different groups of people in North East Asia migrate into America and populate this continent.

Another classic: The Bantu migration from modern day Nigeria/Cameroon area both East and South giving rise to a set of languages (which include Zulu) and adjacent to the East African coast trading migrations/trade that links Arabian pennisular down to Zanzibar and further south

Some "classics" : the Bronze age movement out from the Pontic Steppe (north of the caucasus mountains) both West (into Europe, mixing with Neolithic - stone age - hunter gathers and Anatolian Farmers) and South (into Iran/Pakistan/Northern India).

Pieces like this cheapen genetics (a sort of sci-fi thing to throw into a "this is biological hard wired" sort of discussion) and also cheapen politics (we are destined to disagree and people's minds wont be changed). Both are plain wrong.

So - this is a piece which was written perhaps ... in a post dinner conversation in Bethesda with an evolutionary psycologist and genetics person who caught some ideas about the inherent behaviour of humans and thought it was interesting.

Furthermore with many voting patterns splitting by age (eg Brexit in UK) or Gender (Rep/Dem in mid-terms) or region (SNP - obviously! - but also think Linke) these are also factors that show the big variation in voting behaviour are *not* genetic

When we come to politics, political position change so much (think ... Democrats in the US over the last 50 years, or Liberals/LibDems in the UK, or Green party in Germany) that even if there is some contribution of genetics, it can't be consistent >>

This is independent of known risk factors.  People who with a Titin variant AND mid-wall scarring in their ventricle (on cardiac MR scan) are at especially high risk.
We find that the 10-15% of people with DCM due to a truncating variant in the Titin gene are more likely to have life-threatened arrhythmias, and are also more likely to have atrial fibrillation.

Risk stratification of patients with dilated cardiomyopathy is difficult. Current approaches are poor at identifying people who would benefit from advanced therapies, including implantable defibrillators (ICD).  These are expensive, and cause morbidity, so need to use them wisely

When we plot activity (Phophatase-MAVE/evolutionary sequence energy) vs stability (VAMP-seq/Rosetta ddG) we find that about 60% of the pathogenic variants seem to loose function because of stability, with the remainder appearing to have other mechanisms 9/ https://t.co/y2n86fEpQz

We quantified this using ROC analysis and found that the MAVEs give AUCs that are ~0.1 unit higher than the corresponding computational method, and that methods that probe "activity" give AUCs that are about 0.1 higher compared to those that probe "stability" 8/ https://t.co/2GRC9HtmLu

We compared the scores for a set of pathogenic (ClinVar) variants and variants in gnomAD (in the absence of validated benign variants) and find that all four methods can separate the two classes, though to different extents 7/ https://t.co/Avf4Ewxh0H

We also use Rosetta to predict changes in the thermodynamic folding free energy (ddG) of PTEN. Very roughly, these calculations can be thought to capture similar effects (stability) as the VAMP-seq experiments.  6/ https://t.co/ZshvYUrtNG

In the computational analyses we used GREMLIN to calculate the "evolutionary sequence energy" to assess conservation and whether variants are likely functional. In some way, this computation captures similar effects as the Phosphatase-MAVE experiments.  5/ https://t.co/uzZnQn9bTo
